Utilization of At is not possible with foil-shaped insulating materials, and even the other dielectrics mentioned above cannot be used economically on a large scale, i.e., for large capacitors. Instead an electrolyte solution is employed, which easily adapts to the rough, corrugated surface. A second contact substituting the second electrode in a dielectric capacitor is needed, and it can be established easily by bringing another electronically conducting material with large true surface area (e.g., a roughened aluminum foil or a pellet of activated carbon with some binder) chemically stable towards the electrolyte solution into contact with it. The insulating dielectric material is prepared by forming it as a layer on the first electrode by oxidizing an aluminum foil surface previously roughened by a chemical or electrochemical process, or by oxidizing a porous body of tantalum powder. Al2O3 (εr = 7) is formed in the first case, Ta2O5 (εr = 27) in the second. Both oxides are excellent insulators even at very low thickness (thus enabling the small distance between the two phases: metal and electrolyte solution). The resulting device is a series connection of the dielectric capacitor just described and the double-layer capacitance established at the interface between the electrolyte solution and the second electrode. Because the double-layer capacitance Cdl is much larger than the dielectric one Cdiel the overall capacitance of the device is given by51C=1Cdiel+1Cdl≈1Cdiel.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
